        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pubmed:18228423"/>
          <link xlink:href="pubmed:11121439"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>Gogvadze et al, Curr Protoc cell Biol, 2003
Cancer cells produce most of their ATP through glycolysis
pubmed: 18228423

Matsumara et al, JBC 2000
loss of {Delta}{Psi}m would reduce the cellular ATP level, which may lead to necrotic cell death (Eguchi et al. 1997 Down;  Leist et al. 1997</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="668" y="545" style=""/>
    </node>
    <node id="MPT" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="!BCL2 &amp; ROS:1"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <comment>This corresponds to the permeabilization of apoptotic mitochondria. 
MPT=0 : normal and sane case
MPT = 1:
- Mitochondria responsive to death signals and leading to apoptotic situation
- when signals are too high or cellular conditions not "proper" for apoptosis, then necrosis.</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="672" y="463" style=""/>
    </node>
